# 📋 AWS DCO — Interview Day Execution Checklist

Use this quick-reference guide to make sure you are 100% prepared mentally and technically before heading into your interview loop.

---

## 🌅 Day Before the Interview

- [ ] **Finalize Your 5 STAR Stories:** Review your story matrix in `docs/lp-star-bank.md`. Make sure every story has a clear **Situation, Task, Action, and Result**.
- [ ] **Memorize Your Metrics:** Ensure every STAR story includes hard numbers (e.g., *"reduced host offline time by 20 minutes," "0 dropped packets," "audited 40+ connections"*).
- [ ] **Review the 6-Step Technical Framework:**
  1. Clarify Scope & Impact
  2. Safety First (ESD & LOTO)
  3. Physical Layer First (L1)
  4. Logical Diagnostics & System Logs
  5. Isolate One Variable at a Time
  6. Verify Resolution & Document

---

## ⏰ Morning of the Interview

- [ ] **Test Your Environment:** Ensure your webcam, microphone, lighting, and internet connection are reliable.
- [ ] **Keep a Notepad Ready:** Write down the interviewer's name and the specific question details so you don't forget key constraints.
- [ ] **Mindset Check:** Remember that interviewers want to see how you **think through problems** when you don't know the answer immediately.

---

## 🎯 During the Technical Scenarios

- [ ] **Don't Jump to Conclusions:** Never guess that a component is dead without stating how you will test it first.
- [ ] **Say ESD First:** In *every single* hardware scenario involving physical chassis access, explicitly state: *"First, I will attach my grounded ESD wrist strap..."*
- [ ] **Explain "Why":** When running Linux CLI commands (`dmesg`, `ipmitool`, `ethtool`), state what specific flag or output parameter you are looking for.
